Tokenization converts source text into structured located tokens.
It owns lexical recognition and source-location precision.

The tokenizer should report syntax that is truly lexical or delimiter-shaped.
It should not type-check, resolve imports or decide semantic expression behaviour.

## Main path

`src/compiler_frontend/tokenizer/lexer.rs`

Related path:

- `src/compiler_frontend/numeric_text/` owns shared numeric grammar, normalization, separator/exponent validation and materialisation helpers used by later semantic consumers.

## What tokenization owns

Tokenization owns:

- basic lexical recognition
- source location tracking
- string and template delimiter context
- numeric literal scanning and source-location diagnostics
- attached negative literal classification
- symbolic binary-operator spacing diagnostics
- unary-negation spacing diagnostics
- style directive token recognition through the merged directive registry
- syntax-level rejection of unsupported or unknown directive forms where applicable

The tokenizer consumes literal text and classifies tokens.
Later stages decide semantic numeric type, checked operation behaviour and cast compatibility.

## Entry modes

`TokenizerEntryMode` chooses the initial lexical state for a source file kind.

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Source kind**]
        [: **Tokenizer entry**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Normal `.bst`]
        [: Starts in ordinary code mode.]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Beandown `.bd`]
        [: Starts inside an implicit template body so original source locations can be preserved.]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Plain Markdown `.md`]
        [: Bypasses tokenization because it is a raw content asset.]
    ]
]

`TokenizeMode` is the internal lexical stack state used while scanning nested templates.
It is not the same thing as source-file kind selection.

## Templates and strings

Tokenization handles string/template delimiter context.
It tracks when source is inside code, string or template body text.
That allows later stages to preserve template body text while still detecting invalid boundaries.

Beandown starts inside an implicit template body.
That lets `.bd` files keep real source locations while rejecting an unescaped outer closing bracket.
The compiler does not pretend it prepended wrapper source text.

