## Numeric text

Numeric scanning has two layers:

- the tokenizer consumes and classifies literal source text with source-location diagnostics
- `numeric_text` owns reusable grammar, validation and materialisation helpers for semantic consumers

Keep source text and semantic numeric behaviour separated.
Tokenization can say a literal spelling is invalid.
AST and HIR decide whether a checked numeric operation folds, traps or recovers through builtin `Error!`.

## Style directives

The tokenizer recognises directive tokens through the merged directive registry.
Frontend directives are always available.
Builder directives are added through the active `BackendBuilder`.
Unknown directives are rejected strictly.

Tokenizer and template parsing must use the same merged registry.
Otherwise a directive could tokenize as valid and later parse as unknown, or the other way around.

## Stage 1 and Stage 2 scheduling

In project builds, tokenization is fused with header parsing or source-kind preparation as per-file preparation.

Tiny modules stay serial.
Medium modules cross to per-file Rayon only when source bytes justify the overhead.
Larger modules use chunked Rayon scheduling.

Every strategy produces ordered chunk-local results, then merges string-table deltas and remaps tokens, headers, warnings and diagnostics in original source-file order.
`RAYON_NUM_THREADS` remains the external concurrency control.
The compiler doesn't create a custom frontend Rayon pool.

## What tokenization should not do

Tokenization should not:

- resolve imports
- infer types
- fold constants
- parse declaration shells
- decide template slot semantics
- decide numeric failure mode
- inspect backend feature support beyond directive availability

If a tokenizer change needs semantic facts, the boundary is probably wrong.
